    <note>Liang(1) Rujia [1134] He entered the civil service through the yin of his maternal grandfather, He(2) Zhizhong [8053]. His father-in-law, Ye(1) Jun [4068], was a resident literati (chushi) of the same prefecture. A son, Jiheng [3558], was dismissed as Supervisor of the Temporary Capital Monopoly control bureau and Capital tea market (Tixian Xingzai Juehuo wu Du chachang) in 1179. Rujia's grandson-in-law, Tang(1) Pengju [1590] (a Chuzhou, Qingtian resident), was the grandfather of Jiang(3) Jizhou's [3232] son-in-law, Tang(1) Songyan [3820]. Zhou Bida, WJ, 69.1a-7a; XNYL, 43.16a, 46.15b, 51.8a, 10b, 62.4a, 64.2b-3a, 78.1a, 81.1b, 85.22a, 104.6b, 109.10b, 111.4a, 114.1a, 123.13a, 124.20a, 125.12a, 127.2a, 127.15b, 131.3b, 5a, 132.14b; Xianchun Linan zhi, 50.4b; SHY:ZG, 72.5b-6a; SHY:SH, 47.17b. CBD, 3, 2060-1.</note>
